==English==
===Etymology===
From late Latin [[mammothreptus]], from Greek [[μαμμοθρεπτος]] ‘brought up by one’s grandmother’, from [[μαμμη]] ‘grandmother’ + [[θρεπτος]] verbal adjective from [[τρεφειν]] ‘to bring up’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'mæməθɹɛpt/

===Noun===
'''mammothrept'''
# a [[spoilt]] [[child]]
#:*'''1970''': ‘And having seen the parents I am impatient to see this youth, the fruit of their strangely unattractive loins: will he be a wretched '''mammothrept'''?’ — Patrick O'Brian, ''Master & Commander''